  </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Anyone else feels left out?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Focus items we're a great addition to the game, even if they were poorly inplemented. However, they do nothing to make wizards more group friendly or scale better compared to other classes.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Well, they do a little bit for group friendliness by increasing our sustained damage output over time.  I agree that they don't make us group friendly though.  As far as implmentation, I would argue that the way they were implmented was to help all casters 1-60 immediately.  The real &quot;negative&quot; to how they were implmented effects the level 54+ crowd the worst because there are so few III effects avaliable and the fact that they don't scale up properly (i.e., the best focus item does the same thing as the one you had at level 1).  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Inate crits are merely eye candy. With a 2% chance to do maybe 20% more damage. Why you felt this would be such a great thing is beyond me. They do nothing to improve wizards.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
/boggle<br>
<br>
First off, the very &quot;eye candy&quot; aspects of Innate Crits makes them valuable because these crits effect the &quot;perception&quot; of Wizard damage amongst other classes.  Second, they help increase sustained damage output over time.  Not enough to help grouping, but it still does have an effect.  They can also increase effeciency solo.  You really overstate the case about their uselessness.  I only wish I had them when I was on the treadmill.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> What great fucking AA skills for when your 60! Where we've all decided wizards were great BEFORE these. Do you feel left out? Hell fucking no, because your 60 and have these great AA skills.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
First off, not all of these skills are 60 only.  Second, I was addressing the original post which indicated that someone felt &quot;left out&quot; because all of the attention that Clerics, Druids and Shamans are getting.  My only point was that VI has has paid plenty of attention to Wizards, even if it isn't where you like.  It is worth noting that the &quot;attention&quot; VI has given to Shamans and Druids will have the most effect on the high end game....  <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Now care to get back to the dicussion of the other 99% of the fucking class?<br>
The ones that HAVENT been improved yet.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
99% Hmm.....<br>
<br>
      I think what it comes down to is - should a class be good at everything?  We can all agree that Wizards own solo and own raiding, but suck grouping.  Should we own in all three catagories when no classes excell in all 3?  I would love to see us receive some group enhancements.  If we don't, I don't feel too bad given how exceptional we are solo and raiding.  <br>
<br>
VI has given us attention, alot of attention, even if its not in the 1-59 area.  This attention has taken a class that always &quot;came into its own&quot; at 60, and further increased that power at 60.  <br>
<br>
I expect its about expectiations with you and others.  Maybe its my D&amp;D roots, but I expected to suck at first and have a payoff at the end.  Making 60 post Luclin fulfilled this expectation beyond my, and I expect other's, expectations.  If you expected a different power curve, your probably not very happy.  In closing - <br>
<br>
Given the attention VI has given us, and our power in Raiding and Solo, should we really expect to see much improvement in our Grouping desireability?     <p>60 Sorcerer | The BoD | The Nameless

